BT 1 0 0 1 0 170 Tm /F1 10 Tf 12 TL (Generative Engines comprise two crucial components: a.\) A set of generative models $G = \\{ G _ {) Tj T* (1 } , G _ { 2 } . . . G _ { n } \\}$ , each serving a specific purpose like query reformulation or) Tj T* (summarization, and b.\) A search engine $S E$ that returns a set of sources $\\boldsymbol { S } = \\{) Tj T* (s _ { 1 } , s _ { 2 } . . . s _ { m } \\}$ given a query $q$ . We present a representative workflow in) Tj T* (Figure 2, which, at the time of writing, closely resembles the design of BingChat. This workflow) Tj T* (breaks down the input query into a set of simpler queries that are easier to consume for the search) Tj T* -0.082019 Tw (engine. Given a query, a query re-formulating generative model, $G _ { 1 } = G _ { q r }$ , generates) Tj T* 0 Tw (a set of queries $Q ^ { 1 } = \\{ q _ { 1 } , q _ { 2 } . . . q _ { n } \\}$ , which are then passed to the) Tj T* -0.020983 Tw (search engine $S E$ to retrieve a set of ranked sources $S = \\{ s _ { 1 } , s _ { 2 } , . . . , s _ { m } \\}$) Tj T* 0 Tw (. The sets of sources $S$ are passed to a summarizing model $G _ { 2 } = G _ { s u m }$ , which) Tj T* (generates a summary $S u m _ { j }$ for each source in ??, resulting in the summary set $\( S u m =) Tj T* (\\{ S u m _ { 1 } , S u m _ { 2 } , . . . , S u m _ { m } \\} \)$ . The summary set is passed to a) Tj T* (response-generating model $G _ { 3 } = G _ { r e s p }$ , which generates a cumulative response) Tj T* ($r$ backed by sources ??. In this work, we focus on single-turn Generative Engines, but the) Tj T* (formulation can be extended to multi-turn Conversational Generative Engines \(Appendix A\).) Tj T* ET
